Marie Ferdinand scored 21 points and Margo Dydek sparked a late-game surge to give the Utah Starzz an 83-73
victory over the Washington Mystics on Saturday.
article.headline: Dydek finally gets chance to utilize size
article.linkText: Starzz use giant to help slay Mystics in Washington
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Marie Ferdinand scored 21 points and Margo
Dydek sparked a late-game surge to give the Utah Starzz an 83-73
victory over the Washington Mystics on Saturday.

	   Dydek, the league's tallest player at 7-foot-2, wasn't a factor
in the game's first 28 minutes. Then the Starzz began feeding
her the ball, and she scored 10 and had a key block and assist as
Utah (15-7) took command with a 16-1 run.

	   "Margo finally decided to play and dominated the paint,'' Utah
coach Candi Harvey said. "I thought we played with poise and
didn't let the crowd rattle us.''

	   Dydek scored the first six points of the run and finished with
12 overall as the Starzz snapped a two-game losing streak and
handed Washington (15-7) its second home loss.

	   Utah also got 16 rebounds and 10 points and from Natalie
Williams. Jennifer Azzi added 19 points and Adrienne Goodson had
17. Utah's starters combined for 79 points.

	   "Utah just had answers,'' Washington coach Marianne Stanley
said. "Dydek, down the stretch for them, was huge.''

	   The Starzz also shot 52 percent from the floor (29-for-56) and
91 percent at the line (21-for-23).

	   The Mystics played their eighth straight game without top scorer
Chamique Holdsclaw (ankle) and again missed starting point guard
Annie Burgess (calf). Their offense often struggled, going for long
stretches without a basket in both halves.

	   Washington's Murriel Page scored a career-high 20 points while
Asjha Jones added 14.
